WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.521
Place one ice cube in a sealed, clear bag, set the bag on a plate, and start a timer.

00:00:07.521 --> 00:00:12.667
We can watch without touching very cold water or making a slippery puddle.

00:00:12.667 --> 00:00:17.418
At first the cube has straight edges and keeps its own shape.

00:00:17.418 --> 00:00:22.564
Later, liquid gathers inside the bag and takes the shape of the bottom.

00:00:22.564 --> 00:00:26.523
Something has changed, but let us be precise about what.

00:00:26.523 --> 00:00:29.294
The cube shape is disappearing from view.

00:00:29.294 --> 00:00:31.273
The water is not disappearing.

00:00:31.273 --> 00:00:36.816
Our investigation will track the material called water before, during, and after this change.

00:00:42.316 --> 00:00:46.879
Three words help us untangle the evidence: material, state, and shape.

00:00:46.879 --> 00:00:48.538
Water is the material.

00:00:48.538 --> 00:00:50.613
Solid and liquid are states.

00:00:50.613 --> 00:00:52.687
Cube and puddle describe shapes.

00:00:52.687 --> 00:00:56.836
Before melting, we have solid water in a cube shape.

00:00:56.836 --> 00:01:03.473
After melting, we have liquid water in the shape of the bag and plate beneath it.

00:01:03.473 --> 00:01:06.792
A learner might say, 'The ice is gone.

00:01:06.792 --> 00:01:11.770
' In everyday talk that can mean the solid shape is gone.

00:01:11.770 --> 00:01:17.993
In chemistry, we repair the sentence: the solid state changed, but the water material remained.

00:01:17.993 --> 00:01:22.971
Precise words stop an ordinary change from sounding like matter was destroyed.

00:01:24.371 --> 00:01:28.026
Let us plan a safe time-lapse rather than simply wait.

00:01:28.026 --> 00:01:34.970
Keep the camera still, keep the sealed bag on the same plate, and take one image every two minutes.

00:01:34.970 --> 00:01:38.259
Add a card showing the time in each frame.

00:01:38.259 --> 00:01:44.838
Do not hold the ice against skin, taste the water, or leave melted water where someone could slip.

00:01:44.838 --> 00:01:49.223
An adult can help position the device so it will not fall.

00:01:49.223 --> 00:01:51.416
The changing outline becomes our evidence.

00:01:51.416 --> 00:01:54.705
A time-lapse speeds up playback, not the melting itself.

00:01:54.705 --> 00:02:01.284
It is a record made from separate observations, so gaps between frames are not events we directly saw.

00:02:06.784 --> 00:02:10.084
Now compare the first, middle, and final frames.

00:02:10.084 --> 00:02:13.797
In frame one, nearly all the water is solid.

00:02:13.797 --> 00:02:18.336
In the middle, solid ice and liquid water are both present.

00:02:18.336 --> 00:02:25.762
In the final frame, the visible cube may be gone, yet liquid remains inside the same sealed bag.

00:02:25.762 --> 00:02:31.539
Some water may cling to a fold where the camera cannot show it clearly.

00:02:31.539 --> 00:02:37.727
Still, the labelled, closed setup gives strong evidence against the claim that the water vanished.

00:02:37.727 --> 00:02:43.503
We can describe the change without asking one photograph to tell the whole story.

00:02:44.903 --> 00:02:49.638
Suppose a sensitive balance measures the sealed bag before and after melting.

00:02:49.638 --> 00:02:55.161
If nothing enters, leaves, or spills, the measured mass should stay about the same.

00:02:55.161 --> 00:03:01.473
The material has been conserved: it is still present even though its state and shape changed.

00:03:01.473 --> 00:03:06.207
A balance has limited precision, so the last digit may differ slightly.

00:03:06.207 --> 00:03:10.547
That tiny difference does not mean water was created or destroyed.

00:03:10.547 --> 00:03:14.098
We look for readings that are about the same.

00:03:14.098 --> 00:03:20.015
This balance comparison belongs in an adult-led or app demonstration, not a required home experiment.

00:03:21.415 --> 00:03:24.379
Why does the ice melt on the plate?

00:03:24.379 --> 00:03:29.936
The surroundings are warmer than the ice, so energy is transferred to the colder water.

00:03:29.936 --> 00:03:32.529
We often say the ice gains heat.

00:03:32.529 --> 00:03:39.568
Heat is energy being transferred because of a temperature difference; it is not a substance poured into the cube.

00:03:39.568 --> 00:03:41.791
As energy arrives, melting can occur.

00:03:41.791 --> 00:03:46.977
The room cools by an amount far too small for us to notice here.

00:03:46.977 --> 00:03:51.052
We do not need boiling water, a heater, or a flame.

00:03:51.052 --> 00:03:52.904
Room-temperature surroundings provide a slow,

00:03:52.904 --> 00:03:58.831
low-risk change that is ideal for observation and gives the camera time to collect useful evidence.

00:04:00.231 --> 00:04:03.745
This graph tells a story without advanced maths.

00:04:03.745 --> 00:04:06.381
Time runs from left to right.

00:04:06.381 --> 00:04:09.016
Temperature runs from lower to higher.

00:04:09.016 --> 00:04:12.530
First, the line rises as cold ice warms.

00:04:12.530 --> 00:04:16.922
For pure water, melting happens at about 0 degrees Celsius.

00:04:16.922 --> 00:04:20.436
The line becomes flatter while melting takes place.

00:04:20.436 --> 00:04:27.024
After all the ice is liquid, the line can rise again as the water warms.

00:04:27.024 --> 00:04:30.099
Read the shape: rise, flatter section, rise.

00:04:30.099 --> 00:04:37.126
Our graph is simplified, so real classroom points may wobble instead of making a smooth line.

00:04:37.126 --> 00:04:41.079
We care about the pattern, not calculating a slope.

00:04:46.579 --> 00:04:53.213
A common question is, 'If energy keeps arriving, why does the temperature stop rising for a while?

00:04:53.213 --> 00:04:58.676
' During the flatter part, incoming energy helps change solid water into liquid water.

00:04:58.676 --> 00:05:01.798
It is not mainly making the temperature climb.

00:05:01.798 --> 00:05:06.871
That is why temperature can stay nearly steady while both states are present.

00:05:06.871 --> 00:05:11.554
Once melting is complete, more energy can raise the liquid's temperature again.

00:05:11.554 --> 00:05:18.187
This simple graph shows the main pattern, not every small change that a real thermometer may record.

00:05:19.588 --> 00:05:24.371
We can use a particle model to explain the state change.

00:05:24.371 --> 00:05:31.328
In the solid picture, dots are close together in an organised arrangement and vibrate around positions.

00:05:31.328 --> 00:05:36.546
In the liquid picture, dots remain close but can move past neighbours.

00:05:36.546 --> 00:05:43.068
We keep the same number, colour, and size of dots to represent the same material.

00:05:43.068 --> 00:05:46.981
The model helps us think about arrangement and movement.

00:05:46.981 --> 00:05:49.590
It is not a microscope photograph.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:55.678
Real water particles are not coloured circles, the spaces are not drawn to scale,

00:05:55.678 --> 00:06:00.026
and the model does not show every attraction or collision.

00:06:00.026 --> 00:06:03.939
Its value is explaining evidence, not copying reality exactly.

00:06:05.339 --> 00:06:08.439
Now run the state-change story in reverse.

00:06:08.439 --> 00:06:14.194
Place liquid water in an ice tray and put it in a freezer.

00:06:14.194 --> 00:06:19.949
Energy transfers from the warmer water to the colder surroundings inside the freezer.

00:06:19.949 --> 00:06:22.606
Over time, the liquid becomes solid.

00:06:22.606 --> 00:06:23.934
That is freezing.

00:06:23.934 --> 00:06:29.689
The freezer does not add 'cold stuff'; it helps energy leave the water.

00:06:29.689 --> 00:06:31.903
The material remains water throughout.

00:06:31.903 --> 00:06:38.986
A safe investigation can mark the tray level before freezing and photograph it before and after,

00:06:38.986 --> 00:06:42.085
with an adult handling the freezer space.

00:06:42.085 --> 00:06:46.955
Never taste investigation samples, and never seal water in a rigid,

00:06:46.955 --> 00:06:50.939
completely full container because expanding water can damage it.

00:06:52.339 --> 00:06:55.205
A cooling curve tells the reverse story.

00:06:55.205 --> 00:06:58.479
As liquid water cools, the graph slopes downward.

00:06:58.479 --> 00:07:01.753
Pure water freezes at about 0 degrees Celsius.

00:07:01.753 --> 00:07:07.074
During freezing, the line becomes flatter while liquid and solid are both present.

00:07:07.074 --> 00:07:13.213
After freezing is complete, the solid can cool further and the line slopes down again.

00:07:13.213 --> 00:07:16.078
Read it as fall, flatter section, fall.

00:07:16.078 --> 00:07:20.171
We are not asking for negative numbers or rate calculations.

00:07:20.171 --> 00:07:24.264
We are matching graph regions to events we can observe.

00:07:24.264 --> 00:07:30.403
The graph is simplified, so real freezer readings may wobble instead of following straight lines.

00:07:31.803 --> 00:07:35.138
Ice is not the only solid that can melt.

00:07:35.138 --> 00:07:39.584
Chocolate, butter, and candle wax can also become liquids under suitable conditions,

00:07:39.584 --> 00:07:45.511
but they do not all melt at the same temperature or in exactly the same way.

00:07:45.511 --> 00:07:48.846
Some mixtures soften across a range before they flow.

00:07:48.846 --> 00:07:53.292
For our child-led observation, we stay with sealed ice at room temperature.

00:07:53.292 --> 00:07:58.108
Hot wax can burn skin and must never be heated for this activity.

00:07:58.108 --> 00:08:01.813
Chocolate and butter can be shown in recorded adult demonstrations.

00:08:01.813 --> 00:08:07.370
The transferable question is always: which material are we tracking, what state was it in,

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.963
and what state is it in now?

00:08:15.463 --> 00:08:18.597
When water melts or freezes, it remains water.

00:08:18.597 --> 00:08:22.123
No new material is needed to explain the evidence.

00:08:22.123 --> 00:08:28.391
We call this a physical change: state and appearance change while the substance stays the same.

00:08:28.391 --> 00:08:31.525
Not every change caused by heating is melting.

00:08:31.525 --> 00:08:35.834
Toast browning, paper burning, and an egg cooking make different materials.

00:08:35.834 --> 00:08:39.359
We will not investigate flames or hot cooking here.

00:08:39.359 --> 00:08:43.277
The words 'it got warm' do not name a process.

00:08:43.277 --> 00:08:50.720
Look for evidence that a solid became its own liquid, then ask whether freezing can reverse the state change.

00:08:52.120 --> 00:08:54.362
Let us test three claims.

00:08:54.362 --> 00:08:58.846
Claim one: 'The cube disappeared, so the material was destroyed.

00:08:58.846 --> 00:09:01.536
' Reject it; liquid water remains.

00:09:01.536 --> 00:09:05.572
Claim two: 'The flat graph means no energy enters.

00:09:05.572 --> 00:09:11.402
' Reject it; energy supports the state change while temperature stays nearly steady.

00:09:11.402 --> 00:09:15.886
Claim three: 'Particle dots show exactly what water looks like.

00:09:15.886 --> 00:09:19.473
' Reject that too; dots are model symbols.

00:09:19.473 --> 00:09:25.303
A strong explanation joins evidence and reasoning: the sealed bag still contains water,

00:09:25.303 --> 00:09:32.029
the state changes from solid to liquid, and the simple graph becomes flatter during melting.

00:09:32.029 --> 00:09:34.720
Several clues support one careful conclusion.

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:38.235
Here is the complete story.

00:09:38.235 --> 00:09:44.160
In a safe time-lapse, solid water loses its cube shape and becomes liquid water.

00:09:44.160 --> 00:09:47.545
In a sealed system, the material is conserved.

00:09:47.545 --> 00:09:50.930
Energy transfers from warmer surroundings to colder ice.

00:09:50.930 --> 00:09:55.585
A simple heating curve rises, flattens during melting, then rises again.

00:09:55.585 --> 00:09:58.970
A cooling curve reverses the pattern during freezing.

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:05.317
The particle model shows close particles changing from mostly fixed positions to movement past neighbours,

00:10:05.317 --> 00:10:07.856
but it is not a photograph.

00:10:07.856 --> 00:10:14.204
Whenever an object seems to vanish, ask: what material am I tracking, what evidence remains,

00:10:14.204 --> 00:10:16.320
and did its state change?
